748. Br J Ophthalmol. 1996 Jul;80(7):640-3. doi: 10.1136/bjo.80.7.640.

Life expectancy of diabetic patients undergoing vitreous surgery.

Helbig H(1), Kellner U, Bornfeld N, Foerster MH.

Author information:
(1)Department of Ophthalmology, Universitätsklinikum Benjamin Franklin, Freie 
Universität Berlin, Germany.

BACKGROUND: Patients with advanced diabetic eye disease are commonly in poor 
general health. In addition to the ocular status, life expectancy is an 
important factor in the decision whether and how to perform vitreous surgery. 
The present study investigates mortality and risk factors for survival in 
diabetic patients following vitrectomy.
METHODS: The follow up of 332 consecutive patients who underwent vitrectomy for 
complications of diabetic retinopathy between 1990 and 1994 was studied 
retrospectively. Survival and risk factors for survival were analysed using the 
Kaplan-Meier life table method and for multivariate analysis the Cox 
proportional hazard model.
RESULTS: The 5 year survival rate was 68%. Absence of heart disease was the most 
important predicting factor for survival. Fifty per cent of the patients with 
heart disease had died within 3.5 years. Patients without heart disease had a 5 
year survival rate of 90%. Other significant, independent risk factors were age 
and presence of nephropathy.
CONCLUSION: In diabetic patients undergoing vitrectomy the presence of heart 
disease indicates a poor prognosis for survival. This should be taken into 
consideration for indications and strategies in cases of vitrectomy.

